<TEXT>
the justice department is reviewing a texas 
literacy test for wouldbe law enforcement officers that is failed 
by three out of four blacks and two out of three hispanics 
the federal inquiry is intended to determine whether the test 
discriminates against minorities seeking jobs in nearly 300 texas 
law enforcement agencies 
minority groups tend to be underrepresented in texas law 
enforcement and critics say hiring practices may contribute to the 
prevalence of white faces in blue uniforms 
if the department concludes that the test is discriminatory 
wed have to take appropriate steps to address that problem 
said justice spokeswoman deborah burstionwade 
the test indicates whether a job candidate reads and writes at 
highschool level skills presumed necessary if the candidate is to 
understand the laws being enforced 
one section requires the person to complete a sentence by 
picking the correctly spelled word from three choices other 
sections test grammar 
another section asks the test taker to choose the clearest of 
three sentences discussing the same topic the wrong answers 
contain extremely basic obvious ambiguities said david 
boatright an attorney for the texas commission on law enforcement 
officer standards and education 
the justice department has looked at numerous other state city 
or county writing or reading tests for their effect on minorities 
and employment criteria for physical strength and agility and their 
effect on women 
exams reviewed by the agency have ranged from the suffolk 
county ny county police test to the maryland toll facilities 
police forces height and weight restrictions 
in texas during the past 7 months passing rates were 69 
percent for whites 67 percent for american indians 59 percent for 
asianamericans 36 percent for hispanics and 27 percent for 
blacks 
overall 55 percent of the people who took the test between 
sept 1 1987 and april 21 passed it according to the law 
enforcement standards commission people who fail may repeat the 
exam 
as of feb 17 the state had 41916 licensed law enforcement 
officers 73 percent of whom were black according to the most 
recent figures from the commission 
figures from the 1980 census show 12 percent of texans are black 
the commission had the test developed in the mid1970s and used 
justice department criteria in drafting it 
we offered to run it by the department of justice and they 
refused said attorney boatright were perfectly happy that 
theyre looking at it now 
one of the 283 law enforcement agencies using the test is 
lufkin police chief sherman collins says he doesnt fault the exam 
for the absence of black officers on his force although blacks 
make up about onefourth of the east texas towns population of 
30000 
collins says basic literacy is essential for an officer and to 
help prepare candidates he has enlisted the help of an adult 
learning center which offers preparation for the high school 
general equivalency diploma exam the local agency is offering a 
sixweek course to raise reading comprehension and writing skills 
up to five grade levels collins said 
we want black officers collins said we would have a 
better rapport with the black community if we had black officers 
out there serving them 
only one black out of 13 passed the test in lufkin in june when 
it was offered last the person who passed was a reporter who took 
the exam as part of a news assignment for the lufkin daily news 
</TEXT>
