during last years legislative session 
massachusetts senate president william bulger relegated a 
capitalpunishment bill to committee effectively killing it 
bulger supports the death penalty but he also supports michael 
dukakis and his move spared the governor from having to veto a 
deathpenalty bill 
the incident illustrated how carefully the democratic 
presidential frontrunner is treading when it comes to crime and 
punishment but republican george bush has already attacked dukakis 
on some crime issues and made it clear that theres more criticism 
to come 
at a news conference in sacramento last week bush faulted both 
dukakis and democrat jesse jackson for not supporting the death 
penalty for drug kingpins dukakis opposes the death penalty 
under all circumstances 
another potential point of vulnerability is the massachusetts 
prison system one of the most overcrowded in the country with 
6600 inmates it is 72 percent over capacity the legislature 
pushed by dukakis allocated nearly 1 billion to expand capacity 
but it will take years to ease the overcrowding 
and dukakis ran into a storm of protest last year when william 
horton a convicted murderer walked away from a weekend furlough 
he was arrested later in maryland and convicted of raping a woman 
and beating her husband 
the horton case prompted angry calls for elimination of 
furloughs for firstdegree murderers serving life sentences 
dukakis defended the furlough program for months on grounds 
that it helped prison administrators by giving lifers an incentive 
to behave and gave him a record for judging commutation requests 
but after key members of the legislature deserted him and 
opponents gathered enough signatures to place a furlough ban on the 
fall ballot dukakis reversed himself and dropped his opposition to 
the ban 
dukakis a harvard law school graduate and member of the 
american civil liberties union is generally considered a liberal 
on domestic issues including some criminal matters in addition to 
his opposition to the death penalty he favors controls on handguns 
however dukakis dismayed some liberals when he instituted a 
statewide program of police roadblocks to stop motorists to check 
for drunken drivers he has also backed a bill that would tighten 
criminal sentencing and for the first time in state history 
allow prosecutors to appeal sentences they consider too low 
as governor dukakis created a statewide anticrime council to 
coordinate the efforts of prosecutors judges legislators police 
and citizens dukakis who has never missed one of the councils 
monthly meetings says he would create a similar federal program 
in his campaign literature dukakis touts a 14 percent drop in 
crime in massachusetts since 1983 and the lowest homicide rate of 
any industrial state however most experts attribute the decline 
to the aging of the states population combined with a low 
unemployment rate 
and dukakis doesnt mention the embarrassing fact that 
massachusetts remains the nations auto theft capital 
overall state sen paul harold a democrat who chairs the 
legislatures criminal justice committee gives dukakis high marks 
as an attorney and as someone whos sat in the governors 
chair he has a tremendous overview hes a traditional liberal in 
his theories but if somethings not working he wants to change it 
and get on to the next case harold said 
james fox a professor of criminology at northeastern 
university said governors can actually do little about criminal 
behavior and presidents even less but he said dukakis should be 
credited for his attention to criminal issues he can influence 
when you look at dukakis he appears to have liberal leanings 
but ones that do indeed seem to be supported by facts he said 
