<TEXT>
a small school district plans to embark on an 
experiment that will give teachers greater authority but also 
greater accountability for producing welleducated children 
if approved tonight by the school board and the eastern 
pennsylvania districts 400 teachers the threeyear contract 
extension will give teachers a greater voice in student discipline 
and promotion budgets and school board meetings 
if the teachers new roles do not improve student performance 
the plan and most of the gains teachers stand to make will end with 
the contract extension said william moloney superintendent of the 
easton area school district 
if we find out that dictatorial governance works better then 
by god well do it moloney said but we believe thats not 
true 
the idea called shared governance also calls for creation 
of a labormanagement panel to hear concerns about teacher 
transfers assignments or schedule changes and a master teacher 
panel to recognize superior teachers and to encourage them to 
assist colleagues falling short of expectations 
shared governance says you are a professional and were now 
going to give you control over what you are entrusted to do said 
jo anne bailey a fifthgrade teacher and presidentelect of the 
teachers union 
the plan was proposed by moloney and revised during eight months 
of discussion with principals teachers union representatives and 
school board members 
the contract extension includes significant increases in 
teachers and principals salaries beginning in 1990 moloney said 
the average teacher salary in the district is about 28400 but 
the parties refused to provide specific figures on increases before 
the vote 
known as an advocate for teachers moloney gained their trust 
soon after arriving here in late 1984 in 1985 he won approval of 
a fiveyear contract in a district where bitterness led to strikes 
in 1976 and 1980 
moloney said much of the proposal was based on his 
interpretations of recommendations made in the may 1986 carnegie 
corporation task force report called a nation prepared teachers 
for the 21st century 
some of its recommendations have been tried in rochester ny 
where moloney was assistant superintendent before coming to easton 
large salaries for teachers and limited shared governance have made 
rochester a muchscrutinized laboratory for school reform but 
moloney wanted to go further 
the easton proposal differs by forcing teachers and principals 
to bet major contract provisions on plans scheduled to take effect 
two years later 
all participants the school board teachers and principals 
can veto the plans which include a new evaluation system for 
teachers and administrators and a new program to recognize 
outstanding teachers 
if any provision fails to take effect as scheduled the 
principals forfeit their hefty salary increases and the teachers 
lose their personnel committee for reviewing teacher transfers 
this is serious carrot and stick stuff moloney said 
the pact is part of moloneys larger goal teaching the 
districts 7600 students to read and write add and subtract 
moloney said his plan will mean nothing if it does not produce 
bettereducated children the bottom line is demonstrably 
improved outcome moloney said the name of the game in 
education reform is better outcomes 
