left bank saw aides busily packing up files in cardboard boxes and 
plastic sacks to clear the way for the new premiers staff 
the financial markets responded favorably this morning to the 
election results the french franc was steady to higher in early 
trading while the stock market was steady to higher in calm trading 
shortly after the exchange opened the general market indicator was 
up 106 percent after 30 minutes of trading 
currency traders said the francs steady opening level was 
expected since mitterrands economic policies are not viewed as 
differing widely from chiracs 
mitterrand 71 is the first president elected twice by popular 
vote charles de gaulle was elected in 1958 and 1965 and two other 
men served twice but before a 1962 constitutional amendment 
french presidents always were chosen by indirect election 
unlike 1981 when socialists danced at the bastille to mark a 
historic victory for the left victory celebrations this year were 
subdued mitterrand supporters did honk their car horns along the 
champselysees and 40000 people waved french flags and rallied at 
the place de la republique 
in the first round of elections on april 24 mitterrand won 341 
percent of the vote to lead a field of nine candidates chirac was 
second with 199 percent 
mitterrands election to a new sevenyear term puts an end to 
two years of uneasy cohabitation between a socialist president 
and a rightist premier 
but the immediate future may be even more confusing 
to govern mitterrands premier could form a coalition of 
minority socialists who hold 215 seats in the 573seat parliament 
with some centrist deputies now allied with the right or he could 
ask the president to dissolve the national assembly and hold new 
elections 
more likely the new premier will try to survive as head of a 
minority government without any formal coalition avoiding defeat 
in the hostile assembly by steering clear of controversial issues 
for several months 
the one significant program mitterrands aides have said he 
would pursue is reestablishment of a wealth tax with the proceeds 
used to pay most of the cost of a minimum guaranteed income of 
about 350 per month 
in an interview published friday in the leftist magazine le 
nouvel observateur mitterrand said france needs to increase 
investment in education the economy social programs and the 
building of a united europe 
in all these areas the state has a major role to play he 
said but we cant expect everything from it the final 
responsibility falls to business we need a new generation of 
business leaders who understand that it is the quality of their 
products and the competitivity of their prices that will bring 
success 
but francis perigot head of the french employers association 
said his members will be keeping a close eye on the new 
governments moves 
i will be watching that the next government pursues and 
expands policies favorable to the competitivity of business 
perigot said 
national front leader jeanmarie le pen said sunday that chirac 
was condemned to failure because he refused to do enough to 
attract the fronts extremeright supporters 
the strength of le pen who drew 144 percent of the vote in the 
elections first round increased speculation that some prochirac 
centrists would join a coalition with the socialists 
simone veil health minister under former centerright president 
valery giscard destaing said she saw no problem in principle 
in a governing alliance between centrists and socialists 
many centrist leaders though ruled out supporting a 
socialistled government 
we have absolutely no intention of making a pact of alliance 
with socialism said culture minister francois leotard president 
of the republican party the largest component of the centerright 
union for french democracy coalition 
