<TEXT>
the danish election campaign drew to 
a close monday in a race that could decide the strength of 
denmarks commitment to the nato alliance 
conservative prime minister poul schlueter in a final appeal 
before tuesdays vote said he sought a mandate to restore 
denmarks credibility in the north atlantic treaty organization 
schlueter called the election after he failed to block a move in 
parliament last month to toughen denmarks antinuclear stance the 
move was sponsored by the opposition social democrats 
if implemented the resolution would require denmark to notify 
each visiting warship of denmarks peacetime ban on nuclear weapons 
in its territory 
the resolution was seen as a challenge to natos policy of 
keeping a nuclear option under that policy us and british ships 
refuse to say whether they are armed with nuclear weapons 
schlueter who has led minority governments for six years 
called the snap election on the issue just eight months after the 
last vote 
it was denmarks 19th election since war war ii a european 
record and the first time since then that danes were asked to 
vote mainly on a foreign policy issue 
twelve parties are contesting the election three more than are 
currently represented in the 179member folketing or parliament 
schueters fourparty alliance of centerright parties controls 70 
seats 
schlueter said in an interview published monday that the social 
democrats motion had undermined denmarks credibility with its 
western allies 
this is a referendum about nato he told the conservative 
newspaper berlingske tidende 
he also said he expected a long period of postelection haggling 
to form a workable coalition and that he hoped for a broad 
alliance that would command a majority in parliament 
he did not rule out a partnership with the social democrats 
denmarks largest party 
there is an undeniable need for a group of parties to 
thoroughly discuss the major political problems he said 
i would go so far as to say that it is not advisable to 
appoint a prime minister or a government if there is the least 
doubt that a new majority is behind them schlueter said 
preelection polls indicated another election standoff is 
likely between the two major blocs with the socialliberals again 
holding the balance the party with 11 seats supports the 
government on domestic policy and the opposition on foreign issues 
as many as half a million voters nearly one in eight will 
decide at the last minute how they will vote said ole borre 
political science professor at aarhus university 
many havent decided who they will vote for or whether they 
will vote at all he told berlingske tidende turnout last 
september was 86 percent about average in denmark where 39 
million citizens are registered to vote 
polls show the farright progress party campaigning on a 
platform of deep tax cuts and limiting immigration is the only 
party likely to advance strongly 
in the latest poll published sunday the progress party took 
eight percent compared with the 48 percent it won in the previous 
election 
social democratic leader svend auken has denied that his party 
is antinato and has accused schlueter of exaggerating the meaning 
of the resolution 
auken 44 facing the electorate for the first time as party 
leader is taking over from former prime minister anker joergensen 
who resigned after the last round of balloting 
the social democrats campaigned under the slogan denmark 
decides for itself posters depicting president reagan embracing 
prime minister magaret thatcher implied that the united states and 
britain wanted to dictate denmarks nuclear policies 
the social democrats who dominated danish politics for 40 years 
until they relinquished power in 1982 led denmark into nato as a 
founding member in 1949 
the party drifted toward a hardline antinuclear stance shortly 
after it became the opposition and sponsored a motion to stop 
denmarks payments toward the stationing of cruise missiles in 
europe 
