us aid 
ammunition stockpiles are a central part of army preparedness 
for war the report said the findings of our survey show 
significant malfunctions which must be rectified as soon as 
possible 
comptroller yaacov maltz presented the 983page report at a news 
conference about onefifth of it was devoted to the military 
it said management problems have eroded the profitability of 
israels large weapons industry and investigators could not 
determine exactly what use was made of 18 billion in us 
military aid in 1986 because it was lumped with other 
foreigncurrency expenditures 
maltzs report did not suggest the money was misspent but said 
records of how it was used were inadequate 
some of the budget in foreign currency is allocated along with 
american assistance funds without any differentiation to monitor 
what is being purchased with what money it said 
the comptroller said the investigations conducted last year 
found shortages of essential weapons he blamed them on cuts in the 
defense budget red tape and a need to divert funds to other 
projects he did not name 
his report said surveys found inadequate supplies of 105mm tank 
shells 155mm and 175mm artillery shells and mortars in keeping 
with army regulations no figures were given 
