congressional investigators have determined 
that the immigration and naturalization service is wasting millions 
of tax dollars on unneeded equipment it cannot use a house 
subcommittee chairman said monday 
rep glenn english dokla said a oneyear review by the 
general accounting office found the ins apparently has no 
consistent method of deciding what it needs or how to purchase 
equpment that would fill those needs the result is that at best 
were getting equipment that doesnt really do the job 
the ins responded monday to concerns raised in the report with 
plans to establish a research and development steering committee 
that will develop procurement procedures based on some gao 
recommendations said spokesman verne jervis 
the ins planning office which includes research and 
development will also be moved so that it reports directly to the 
ins commissioners office where it will receive enhanced 
visibility and increased access to top management jervis said 
english said he was concerned efforts in the war on drugs were 
being hurt by the ins apparent waste of millions of dollars on 
equipment the ins cant really use 
theres no question that ins and particularly the border 
patrol are underfunded when it comes to the war on drugs 
therefore money wasted on unwise purchases is money that cannot be 
used to halt the flow of drugs across our borders he said in a 
statement 
the gao report to be released thursday at a hearing by 
englishs government information justice and agriculture 
subcommittee found that the ins had no defined formal method of 
technology selection 
in one instance the gao found the ins had ordered the purchase 
of 11 undercover vans outfitted with an extendable infrared scope 
for monitoring the us borders at a cost of more than 130000 
for each vehicle even though operational tests were incomplete 
and the report said the infrared scopes which could have been 
used to support linewatch operations in various border patrol 
sectors sat unused for at least 7 months at fort huachuca ariz 
