<TEXT>
the united states cannot afford from a 
military perspective to fall further behind in its star wars 
research the pentagon said monday 
the defense department in a required annual report on the 
strategic defense initiative or star wars program said even 3 
percent annual increases in funding for the research would not be 
enough to keep pace with the soviet union 
the russians continue to modernize their offensive as well as 
defensive weaponry gradually improving their ability to destroy 
us forces with a surprise attack the pentagon report said 
the resulting asymmetry between soviet and us forces has led 
to a destabilizing situation one that must be redressed the 
pentagon said 
a star wars defense system that could shoot down soviet missiles 
offers the promise of a more stable peace the pentagon insisted 
the mere process of attempting to develop such a system complicates 
soviet military planning and strains the russian economy 
if on the other hand congress continues to cut deeply into 
star wars funding the united states will not only waste its 
greatest leverage the innovation possible in a free society but 
it cannot expect to do more than react to soviet initiatives in 
strategic defense the pentagon said 
we are faced with either delaying the time when a decision on 
whether to deploy defenses could be made or eliminating some 
technology efforts thereby reducing the number of defense options 
that can support a decision 
the pentagon included the new plea for funding in a report that 
runs to several hundred pages reviewing the work done over the 
past year in various technological fields 
release of the report comes just a week after defense secretary 
frank c carlucci warned he would recommend that president reagan 
veto the pentagons fiscal 1989 budget bill if cuts are made to the 
45 billion requested for star wars 
while the administration has been forced to abandon its goal of 
increasing overall defense spending by 3 percent a year it 
continues to request steep hikes for star wars since 1983 
however congress has cut almost 5 billion from the roughly 18 
billion requested for star wars 
while the congress has increased star wars funding every 
year the difference between what the administration has requested 
and what the congress has appropriated is so large that it has had 
a substantial and increasingly detrimental impact on the program 
the defense department asserted 
