<TEXT>
a study of schizophrenics brains suggests a 
possible answer to a decadesold mystery about an abnormality 
associated with the illness a researcher said monday 
brain scans of 17 living patients pinpointed a site of a 
reduction in brain tissue that apparently produces enlargement of 
normal brain cavities said richard suddath of the national 
institute of mental health 
the enlargement of the fluidfiled spaces called ventricles 
had been observed since the 1930s but nobody has known which part 
of the brain produces it he said 
failure of part of the brain to develop or shrinkage could 
produce the enlargement he said 
if the new finding is confirmed it points the way to an 
anatomical target for further study of schizophrenia he said 
suddath spoke to reporters at the annual meeting of the american 
psychiatric association he did the work with colleagues at the 
mental health institute 
the brain scans using a technique called magnetic resonance 
imaging found an average of a 20 percent reduction in the gray 
matter of the temporal lobes compared with the volume found in 17 
normal people of similar age and size 
the temporal lobes lie beneath the temples on each side of the 
head 
the less temporal lobe gray matter a patient had the larger his 
lateral ventricles tended to be implicating that tissue was at 
least part of the explanation for enlargement of the ventricles 
suddath said 
researchers do not know when the reduction in gray matter 
appears in comparison to when schizophrenia appears he said it 
may be a failure of the tisue to develop before birth or around the 
time of birth he said 
daniel freedman director of the division of adult psychiatry at 
the university of california los angeles neuropsychiatric 
institute noted that the study included few patients 
its too soon to say whether it will pay off in better 
diagnosis or predicting response to treatment he said 
but it is a promising start in using magnetic resonance 
imaging to seek clues to brain abnormalities in schizophrenia he 
said 
</TEXT>
