<TEXT>
 
editors note in a program that began under president lyndon 
johnson more than 300 white house fellows have spent a year 
working in various federal departments and agencies learning the 
ways of government from within some have stayed and now occupy 
high posts in the government others have gone home but with a 
different outlook 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
in the old executive office building next door 
to the white house james l nuzzo scans column after column of 
numbers in a budget book and prepares a memorandum for vice 
president george bush 
nuzzo is a neurologist from boston 
over at the agriculture department george m drysdale makes his 
way through the intricacies of farm price supports soil 
conservation and consumer services 
drysdale is a venture capitalist from san francisco 
in the office of the us trade representative karen s 
kellerhouse fields inquiries from mayors and governors about us 
foreign trade policy 
ms kellerhouse is a financial executive on leave from the port 
authority of new york and new jersey 
nuzzo drysdale and ms kellerhouse are among a dozen americans 
in their early or middle 30s who are working as white house fellows 
in a program that has survived from lyndon johnsons great society 
to ronald reagans new american revolution 
since 1965 more than 300 of them have passed through 
washington spending 12 months working in federal departments and 
agencies to learn the ways of government some have stayed and 
occupy high posts in the government others have gone home 
white house fellows work at the national aeronautics and space 
agency the department of energy the pentagon the office of 
management and budget the justice department the arms control and 
disarmament agency and in the white house 
of the current crop one is a newspaper marketing executive 
three are attorneys one is vice president of a scientific products 
firm three are army majors one a captain in the marine corps 
during their septemberthroughaugust stint for which they were 
chosen from among about 800 applicants they receive a salary of up 
to 55000 a year officials say most of them successful in their 
own careers absorb a pay cut anyone is eligible except federal 
civil servants 
some of the programs graduates have big offices in washington 
lt gen colin l powell who worked as a fellow under thenbudget 
director caspar weinberger in 197172 is now president reagans 
national security adviser another alumnus michael h armacost is 
undersecretary of state for political affairs 
another david karnes says i wouldnt be united states 
senator today if it werent for the white house fellows program 
the nebraska republican is one of two who have made it to the 
senate tim wirth a fellow in the department of health education 
and welfare in 196768 is a democratic senator from colorado 
henry g cisneros of the class of 197172 is mayor of san 
antonio joe barton 8182 is a representative from texas garry 
carruthers 7475 is governor of new mexico tom johnson 
6566 is publisher of the los angeles times james k stewart 
8182 is director of the national institute of justice robert 
haas 6869 is president of levi strauss company doris kearns 
met lyndon johnson when she was a fellow and became his biographer 
several former fellows are generals or admirals 
it all started in 1957 with john gardner then president of the 
carnegie foundation for the advancement of teaching 
i had been doing quite a bit of reading about the founding 
fathers and i was struck with the fact that just about every single 
one of them had very early opportunity to observe government 
gardner recalls it was right across the street so to speak the 
government of their colony he also found he says that the 
ablest kids in the country today never saw anybody governing 
i wrote a memo proposing the idea of a group of white house 
fellows and had the idea that it could be financed by 
foundations he said the only problem was the bill was very 
high and there wasnt any foundation interested in it 
seven years later gardner was having lunch with eric goldman a 
princeton university historian then an aide to president johnson 
goldman said johnson was concerned that too few young people were 
interested in government 
look ive got a memo says gardner who would later become 
johnsons secretary of health education and welfare goldman 
showed the memo to the president and first lady lady bird johnson 
and the program was launched 
today it has a budget of slightly less than 500000 a year 
supplemented by private funds raised by a foundation set up by 
former fellows 
in its early years the program was limited to applicants 
between the ages of 24 and 36 but the age requirement was 
abandoned in response to an antidiscrimination suit all of the 
current fellows however would have qualified under the original 
limits 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880509-0209 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the youngest fellow in history david neuman was 23 when he 
served in the white house office of cabinet affairs neuman says 
the experience has been very useful and helpful in his present 
job vice president for current comedy programs at nbc 
relationships between the white house and the departments and 
agencies are much like that between a television network and the 
various studies and production companies he says the 
political dynamic is very similar 
neuman says the program needs to be better publicized 
everybody knows what the rhodes scholarship is and very few 
people know what the white house fellowship is 
applications are first reviewed at a january reunion of alumni 
who cut them to about 130 those applicants are invited to travel 
at their own expense to 11 cities to be interviewed by panels of 
prominent citizens 
this cuts the field to 33 who come to washington at government 
expense for a weekend for more interviews by members of the 
presidentially appointed commission on white house fellowships 
