<TEXT>
when clarence fountain was 9 years old he 
joined a gospel troupe called the happyland jubilee singers nearly 
50 years later he is still praising the lord in song 
he and the group now called clarence fountain and the five 
blind boys of alabama are appearing in the musical the gospel at 
colonus the show sets sophocles tale of oedipus the king within 
the framework of a black pentecostal church service and its rousing 
gospel music 
i learned most of my gospel singing in school says 
fountain sitting backstage at broadways luntfontanne theater 
where colonus is playing his school which went from grades 
one through 12 was the talladega institute for the deaf and blind 
in talladega ala 
fountain who has been blind since he was 2 sang in the school 
choir but gospel music was a part of his life even before that 
his father was a steward in a methodist church in selma ala 
i was the only one in the family who sang though he says 
it became something that grows on you 
the happyland jubilee singers continued to perform after 
fountain and the other members left school early to perform during 
the mid1940s in 1947 they moved to chattanooga tenn where 
they had a 15minute gospel broadcast each weekday at 645 am 
the name five blind boys of alabama was born the following 
year courtesy of a newark nj promoter who began to manage the 
troupe the blind boys would play onenight stands all over the 
country appearing in schools churches and auditoriums they 
eventually worked their way up to such places as the apollo theater 
and carnegie hall in new york and made a lot of records 
one of their songs precious lord take my hand was a best 
seller in 1953 it was a touching song fountain recalls 
people responded 
we always sang gospel fountain says that was the big 
thing you couldnt sing rock n roll and then turn around and 
sing gospel people wouldnt follow you 
a lot of those people singing rock n roll started by 
singing gospel in church people like sam cooke and aretha 
franklin there were a lot of them thats why they can sing it so 
good 
today fountain says there is a contemporary gospel sound 
religious music that has a rock n roll beat the five blind boys 
have adapted to it 
you have to keep up with the style fountain says if you 
dont keep up with the style youre automatically behind the 
times 
fountain writes some of the groups songs with sam butler who 
plays guitar for the troupe 
writing songs is just like writing a poem fountain says 
as long as it rhymes and comes out right you can take any poem 
and turn it into a song 
if fountain gets an idea for a song he turns it over in his 
head memorizes it and then tells butler who writes it down 
it was through butler that fountain and the blind boys met 
composer bob telson and director lee breuer the creators of the 
gospel at colonus 
they had the lyrics and the tunes but they didnt have the 
ingredients to go along with it fountain says its just like 
cookin bread you got the bread but you dont have the salt so it 
dont taste like bread we put the salt in 
the show has played at the walker art center in minneapolis and 
in 1983 at the brooklyn academy of music as well as all over europe 
before tackling broadway 
the gospel at colonus stars actor morgan freeman who 
narrates the church service and it features several other gospel 
groups such as jj farley and the soul stirrers and the jd 
steele singers 
but the blind boys get to sing in the evenings two 
showstopping numbers no never and lift me up they bring 
down the house 
its easier to do than a concert fountain says with a 
concert you dont rest you have to really get down in the 
musical we get a chance to breathe a little 
today fountain who has been married three times makes his 
home in detroit the rest of the blind boys live all over the 
country from north carolina to minnesota before a concert tour 
starts they all meet to rehearse their material and then hit the 
road fountain and the rev olice thomas are the only original 
members of the group still performing 
we all have good ears he says if it doesnt sound right 
we just leave it alone we all agree on one thing if it sounds 
good to us we cut a record 
my dream was to sing to the masses of people and when this 
play came along that was my dream and its happening just like i 
dreamed it would weve come a long way from the sticks to 
broadway 
</TEXT>
